When doing concurrency in C++, a lock can be a local variable that is used to synchronize access to a shared resource.

A lock is typically a mutex or a semaphore that is used to ensure that only one thread can access the shared resource at a time. When a thread wants to access the shared resource, it acquires the lock by calling a lock method on the mutex or semaphore. Once the thread is finished accessing the shared resource, it releases the lock by calling an unlock method on the same mutex or semaphore.

A lock can be a local variable in a function or method because it is only needed for the duration of the critical section in which the shared resource is accessed. When the lock variable goes out of scope, its destructor is automatically called, which releases the lock on the shared resource.

For example, consider the following code:

```
#include <mutex>
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

std::mutex m;

void printThreadID(int id) {
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m);
    std::cout << "Thread ID: " << id << std::endl;
}

int main() {
    std::thread t1(printThreadID, 1);
    std::thread t2(printThreadID, 2);
    t1.join();
    t2.join();
    return 0;
}
```

In this code, a local variable `lock` of type `std::lock_guard<std::mutex>` is used inside the `printThreadID` function to acquire and release the lock associated with the `m` mutex. The `std::lock_guard` is a simple wrapper around a mutex that automatically acquires and releases the lock when the lock_guard object goes out of scope.

When the `printThreadID` function is called by each thread, the lock is acquired on the shared resource (which is the standard output stream, in this case) using the `std::lock_guard` object, which is a local variable. When the `printThreadID` function returns, the `std::lock_guard` object goes out of scope, and its destructor is called, which releases the lock on the shared resource.

In summary, using a lock as a local variable simplifies resource management in concurrent programming by ensuring that resources are automatically released when they are no longer needed, which avoids potential deadlocks and race conditions.

